sex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England"},"en":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"about 1420–after 1450","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1450–1507":"1450–1507","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","after 1450":"after 1450","1507":"1507","abt 1420":"about 1420","about 1450":"about 1450","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","England":"England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gillard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Gillard</i>, <i>Jillard</i>, with initial soft <i>g</i> (/dʒ/), a borrowing of Old French <i>Gillard</i>, a pet form of <i>Gille</i> (see   Giles   and 4 below). Alternatively, from the Middle English personal name <i>Gillard</i> which, with a hard <i>g</i> (/g/), would be from Old French <i>Guilard</i>, corresponding to the Norman form   Willard  .","English: sometimes perhaps an altered form of   Gillett  .","English: sometimes perhaps an altered form of   Gerard   (Middle English <i>Girard</i>) with <i>r/l</i> substitution."],"variants":[{"name":"Giles","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from a medieval personal name, Middle English <i>Giles</i> or <i>Gile</i>, a borrowing from Old French <i>Gil(l)e(s)</i>. This is from Latin <i>Aegidius</i> and this presumably from Greek <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’ (alternatively, it could be a Late Latin formation from the Latin personal name <i>Eggius</i> + the suffix <i>-idius</i>). The personal name was widely used in France and the Low Countries, partly through veneration of Saint Gilles de Provence, supposedly a hermit of the 7th century near Arles; he was patron saint of cripples, hence the dedication of Saint Giles Cripplegate in London, though the personal name itself was less common in England than elsewhere in Europe. See also   Gilles  .","Irish: adopted as an Anglicized equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Glaisne</b>, a County Louth name based on <i>glas</i> ‘green, blue, gray’.","French: variant of   Gilles  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Izzard","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English and Old French female personal name <i>Iseld</i>, <i>Iseut</i>, <i>Isalt</i>, <i>Isaut</i>, <i>Isolde</i>, <i>Isoud</i>, a French adaptation of Old Cornish <i>Eselt</i> ‘looked up to, admired’. Its currency in post-Conquest England derived from the legend of Tristan and Isolde, Cornish versions of which gained huge popularity in medieval Europe through romantic retellings by German, French, and Anglo-Norman writers.","from the Middle English female personal name <i>Isot</i>, itself a pet form of <i>Iseld</i>, <i>Isold</i>, names formerly but incorrectly identified as a hypothetical ancient Germanic <i>Ishild(is)</i>, developing to <i>Isheld</i>, <i>Ishaut</i>, and <i>Isholt</i>. The surname <i>Izzard</i> shows post-medieval substitution of <i>-ard</i> in the final syllable of Middle English <i>Iso(u)d</i> (see 1 above) or <i>Isot</i>, influenced by the pattern of variation in names like   Gillard  ,   Gillett  , and   Gillott  , or   Garrard  ,   Garrod  , and   Garrett  , where in many instances the final <i>-ard</i> is original. Compare   Ezzard  ,   Isard  ,   Isitt  ,   Izard  , and   Izatt  ."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah Gillard was born about 1420, in England. She had at least 1 daughter with Edward Warren Baker. She died after 1450, in her hometown."},"et":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"umbes 1420–pärast 1450","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1450–1507":"1450–1507","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","after 1450":"pärast 1450","1507":"1507","abt 1420":"umbes 1420","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","England":"England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"noin 1420–1450 jälkeen","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1450–1507":"1450–1507","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","after 1450":"1450 jälkeen","1507":"1507","abt 1420":"noin 1420","about 1450":"noin 1450","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","England":"England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England"},"fr":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"environ 1420–après 1450","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1450–1507":"1450–1507","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","after 1450":"après 1450","1507":"1507","abt 1420":"environ 1420","about 1450":"environ 1450","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sarah Gillard est née environ 1420, à Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Edward Warren Baker. Elle est décédée après 1450, dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"um 1420–nach 1450","1420–1450":"1420–1450","1450–1507":"1450–1507","1420":"1420","1450":"1450","after 1450":"nach 1450","1507":"1507","abt 1420":"um 1420","about 1450":"um 1450","Culmstock, Devon, England":"Culmstock, Devon, England","England":"England","Steyning, Sussex, England":"Steyning, Sussex, England","lifeSummary":"Sarah Gillard wurde um 1420 in England geboren. Sie hatte mit Edward Warren Baker mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb nach 1450 in ihrem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"abt 1420–after 1450":"about 1420–after 1450